***  (x) 3. Operational Requirements

     - Requirements:
       1. The GPS spoof detection system shall identify GPS spoofing as it occurs to the aircraft GPS tracking systems while in operation. 
       2. The GPS spoof detection system shall have a red light that allows users to identify if they are a target of spoofing while in operation.  
       3. The GPS spoof detection system shall store a record of all GPS spoof attacks while in operation.  
       4. The GPS spoof detection system shall be able to have data transferred off platform while not in operation.  
       5. The GPS spoof detection system shall communicate with aircraft GPS systems while in operation. 
       6. The GPS spoof detection system shall interface with current aircraft electrical power systems while in operation. 
       7. The GPS spoof detection system shall perform a Built-in Test to verify operational integrity every 1 minute while in operation. 
       8. The GPS spoof detection system shall display a visual alert within 3 seconds after catching a possible GPS spoof attack while in operation. 
       9. The GPS spoof detection system shall emit a sound alert within 3 seconds after catching a possible GPS spoof attack while in operation. 
       10. The GPS spoof detection system shall have a button for the user to cancel the alert while in operation. 

     - Key Performance Parameters (KPPs)
       1. Spoof Detection Accuracy (KPP-1) - the primary function of the system is to detect spoofing attacks. High accuracy is critical to avoid false positives and false negatives, ensuring mission success and safety. 
       2. Response Time (KPP-2) - Rapid alerting is essential for pilots to take immediate countermeasures. A maximum of 3 seconds is set as the threshold, with an objective of 1 second for optimal performance. 
       3. Reliability (KPP-3) - Continuous operation is necessary, requiring reliability to ensure functionality even in the event of partial system failure. 
       4. Power Consumption (KPP-4) - The system must be efficient and work within the aircraft’s power constraints, with a backup option to maintain functionality during electrical failures. 
       5. User Interface Clarity (KPP-5) - Pilots must be able to interpret alerts quickly and effectively. A simple, clear interface reduces cognitive load and improves reaction time. 

