***  (x) 7. Technical Performance Measures

     As the GPS Spoof Detection System progressed from concept to implementation, we established and refined a set of Technical Performance Measures (TPMs) to guide our engineering decisions, validate requirements, and mitigate technical risk. These TPMs were not just abstract metrics; they became the backbone of our iterative design, the justification for our trade-offs, and the checkpoints for assessing operational value. 

     Throughout development, each TPM aligned directly with one or more operational requirements and system objectives. Below, we present the five most critical TPMs, explaining their importance, how they evolved over time, and the system requirements they support 

     - TPM #1 - Time to detect spoofing attack 
     The time it takes from the start of a GPS spoofing event to the moment the system identifies it as a threat. 
     In aviation, seconds matter. The faster we detect an attack, the more time the flight crew or automated systems has to respond. Our target of 3 seconds ensures timely alerts and preserves system credibility. 
     Early prototypes averaged 5.2 seconds; by integrating faster signal filters and optimizing anomaly thresholds, we reduced this to 2.6 seconds, with consistent performance in simulation. 
     Traceability supports Requirement #8 and #9: visual and audible alerts within 3 seconds. 

     - TPM #2 - Spoofing detection accuracy 
     The percentage of actual spoofing attacks the system correctly identifies (true positives). 
     High accuracy is the foundation of trust. Pilots and engineers must rely on the system to catch real threats, especially in contested airspace. Our goal of greather than 95% accuracy ensures the system adds real safety value. 
     Initial models achieved only 84%, but successive training on a broader spoofing signal dataset increased this to 92.3%. Final testing is projected to exceed 95%. 
     Traceability supports Requirement #1: detect spoofing in real time; informs system certification performance 

     - TPM #3 - Power consumption 
     The average power draw of the detection system during steady-state operation. 
     Integration with legacy and modern aircraft platforms requires compliance with tight power budgets. Our cap of less than 40W ensures broad compatibility without additional retrofitting. 
     Baseline components originally consumed 44W; we brought this down to 38W by selecting low-power processors and optimizing idle modes. 
     Traceability directly supports Requirement #6: interface with aircraft electrical systems 

     - TPM #4 - False Positive Rate 
     This was introduced during preliminary testing. The percentage of normal GPS activity incorrectly flagged as spoofing. 
     Excessive false alerts degrade user trust and may lead to alert fatigue. We set a target of ≤3% to balance sensitivity and operational reliability. 
     Early thresholds led to a false positive rate of 6.1%. We improved this by refining our detection logic using multi-factor analysis, now bringing false positives under 3.5%. 
     Traceability supports Requirement #10: include an alert cancel function, anticipating potential user intervention. 

     - TPM #5: Data Logging Uptime  
     The percentage of time the system is successfully logging spoofing-related data during operation. Persistent, reliable data logging is critical for validation, regulatory compliance, and post-event analysis. We established a performance floor of greater than 99.5% uptime. 
     Logging uptime improved from 95% (due to memory buffer overflow errors) to 99.7% after restructuring our data write intervals and adding a backup buffer. 
     Traceability supports Requirement #3: record all spoofing events while in operation 

     Our system’s evolution is shaped by these TPMs, from concept to near-certification. More than just technical metrics, they served as measurable commitments to reliability, safety, and integration viability. The next stage of development will include operational flight testing, where these measures will be validated under real-world conditions. 

***  (x) 8. MOEs & MOPs
     - need to understand what to do here

     MOE -> Measures of Effectiveness
     Assess how well the GPS spoofing detection system achieves its mission objectives, focusing on its ability to protect users or systems
     from spoofing attacks in operational scenarios

     - Example 1: Percentage of spoofing attacks successfully detected and reported.
       This MOE measures the proportion of spoofing attempts that the system correctly identifies and alerts the user or system about, indicating its effectiveness in ensuring navigational integrity.
     - Example 2: Time to detect and alert on a spoofing attack.
       This MOE evaluates how quickly the system can identify a spoofing attempt and issue an alert, reflecting its effectiveness in time-sensitive operational environments.

     MOP: Measures of Performance
     Focus on the technical performance of specific system components or functions, measuring how well the detection system operations

     - Example 1: Sensitivity of signal anomaly detection.
       This MOP measures the system's ability to detect deviations in GPS signal characteristics (e.g., timing, power, or modulation inconsistencies), ensuring it can identify spoofed signals with high accuracy.
     - Example 2: False positive rate of spoofing detection.
       This MOP evaluates the percentage of legitimate GPS signals incorrectly flagged as spoofed, ensuring the system minimizes unnecessary alerts and maintains user trust.

     OUR MOEs and MOPs:
     MOE:
     - Navigation in Contested Environments
     - Post-Mission Intelligence
     - Pilot Situational Awareness
     - Mission Continuity
     - System Integration & Readiness

     MOP:
     - Detection Accuracy, Time to Detect
     - Event Logging, BIT result storage
     - UI Clarity, Red Light, Sound Alerts
     - Spoof confirmation and alert speed
     - Install Time, Power Draw

